  <h1 class="page-title">about</h1>

  <article class="prose">
    <p>
      I'm Cyrus (<span lang="fa" dir="rtl">کوروس</span>, Kuros in Persian,
      which is where the domain comes from), a staff software engineer at
      Meta in New York, working on ads ranking AI.
    </p>
    <p>
      My lane is ranking systems, recommenders, and the infrastructure
      that keeps applied ML honest. Over the past decade that has included
      recommenders at Dollar Shave Club, LLM fine-tuning at Google, the
      ML platform at HBO Max, and ranking models that serve billions of
      people at Meta.
    </p>
    <p>
      I also spent four years in engineering management, the last two
      running a 15 engineer ads ranking team at Meta. In May 2026 I went
      back to building on purpose. The first month back I shipped a
      computer vision pipeline for NBA broadcast video; the next, an
      always-on agent that takes orders over iMessage. Management
      taught me what unreliable systems cost a team, which is probably
      why everything I build now has to show its evidence or abstain.
    </p>

    <h2>ranking at meta scale</h2>
    <p>
      The specifics of the ads work are Meta's, but the shape of the
      problems is public: calibration under delayed and biased feedback,
      exploration against a live auction, multi-task value models,
      latency budgets measured in milliseconds, and launch discipline
      where every change has to prove itself against a holdout. A decade
      of ranking and recommender work, the recent stretch at that scale,
      turns out to be good preparation for frontier model work, because
      reward models are ranking models. Pairwise preference, calibration,
      evals that catch a model being confidently wrong: same math,
      higher stakes.
    </p>

